{"id":"1606.01877","submitter":"Yves Aur\\'egan","authors":"Yves Auregan and Maaz Farooqui and Jean-Philippe Groby","title":"Low frequency sound attenuation in a flow duct using a thin slow sound\n  material","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1121/1.4951028","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a thin subwavelength material that can be flush mounted to a duct\nand which gives a large wide band attenuation at remarkably low frequencies in\nair flow channels. To decrease the material thickness, the sound is slowed in\nthe material using folded side branch tubes. The impedance of the material is\ncompared to the optimal value, which differs greatly from the characteristic\nimpedance. In particular, the viscous and thermal effects have to be very small\nto have high transmission losses. Grazing flow on this material increases the\nlosses at the interface between the flow and the material.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Oct 2015 13:05:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-06-29"}
